SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt recv vax 16OCT97 & the next day pt exp SOB, nausea, chills, sweats, h/a, dizziness, stiff neck, general myalgia & malaise;sx have occurred w/increasing severity p/each vax; It was reported that a 34-year-old female was vaccinated with RAB-IMOVAX Rabies on October 16, 1997 as the fourth dose of a post exposure treatment series. The next day the patient experienced shortness of breath, nausea, chills, sweats, headache, dizziness, stiff neck, general nyalgia and malaise. The patient has been in contact with her physician regarding these symptoms. The patient reports that the symptoms have occurred with increasing severity following each vaccine dose of the treatment series. From follow-up #1, November 7, 1997, the recovery status of the patient was not reported and remains unknown. From Follow-up correspondence received at Manufacturer on 18-Apr-2000, it was reported that the patient recovered from this experience. The patient had paranoid schizophrenia and this impairs comunication at times, she had recovered from bite and reaction.
HISTORY: Iodine; Morphine; Suffers from paranoid and schizophrenia

Pt recv vax on unknown day; post vax pt exp transient numbness and could not walk for a few hr This is a follow-up to report (s) previously submitted on 1/25/99. Informaiton has been received form a physician concerning a 11 month old male patient with recent otitis and BACTRIM allergy who on 01-DEC-1998 was vaccinated with a third dose of COMVAX vaccine IM. Concomitant vaccination that same day included the first dose of VARIVAX vaccine (MSD) SC. That same day, the patietn experienced "transcient numbness and couldn't walk for a few hours." There was no locala tenderness, erythema, or swelling noted. Later that day the patient awoke crying from his nap. The patietn sought unspecified medical attention. On 02-DEC-1998 the patient recovered form his experiences. It was reported that another patient had a similar experience (WAES#98121251). No further informaiton is available.

pt recv vax 2JAN98 & 2hr post vax pt devel a rough, non-pruritic rash w/heat all over body x/hands, fever of 103.5,malaise & arthralgias which required an ER or MD visit;dx vasculitis; This is a follow-up to report (s) previously submitted on 03/01/1999. Information has been received from a health care professional concerning a 36 year ol female with no known allergies and a history of hepatitis b exposure and gfestational diabetes mallitus, who in 1992 was vaccinated with the entire series of RECOMBIVAX vaccine. In October 1997, the patient "had an sxposure". Antibody evaluation "at the time" was negative. On 02-JAN-1998 the patient was vaccinated with a fourth dose of RECOMBIVAX IM in the left deltoid. Approximately two hours post-vaccination, the patient developed a rough, non-pruritus rash "with heat" all over her body except her hands, afever of 103.5 malaise, myalgias and arthralgias which required an emergency room or physician's visit. On 06-JAN-1998, the following laboratory values wre noted: serum glucose 107, A/G ratio 1.1, AST 49 and ALT 66.That same day, the patient was diagnosed with vasculitis. She was treated with PREDNISONE (Sterapred DS) at that time. On 09-JAN-1998, her arthralgia symptoms worsened. PREDNISONE was stopped and TAGAMET and ALLEGRA were ordered. The patient improved at that time. At some time during this condition , serum glucose was 144. On 16-JAN-1998, all laboratory values were  within normal limits. The reporter also noted that the patient did not recover. Follow-up information received from ahealth care professinal indicated that on 19-JAN-1999 the patient recovered from her experiences and subsequently returned to work. No further information is available.
LAB_DATA: 6JAN98 anion gap 1.1;serum alanine aminotrans 66;serum aspartate aminotra 49;serum glucose 144;serum glucose 107;serum hepatitis B (e) ant negative p/3 doses. This is a follow-up to report (s) previously submitted on 03/01/1999. Informaiton has been received from a registered nurse concerning a 12 year old female with a history of an ear infection one week prior to vaccination who on 02-DEC-1997 and 02-JAN-1998 was vaccianted IM with the first and second doses of RECOMBIVAX vaccine. Concomitant vaccines on 02-JAN-1998 includes diphteria + tetanus toxoids vaccine. On the same day as vaccination, the patient experienced arthralgia wiith pain in both shoulders. On approximately 06-JAN-1998 the patient experienced a rash on the arms with papules .5 mm to 5 mm in size. The papules were light in color. She was seen in a physician's office on 05-FEB-1998. She also had otitis media at the time of the office visit. The rash began to worsen on approximately 11-FEB-1998. The patient was initially administered and antifungal cream, but it was inefective. On 18-FEB-1998 the rash was "all over" the arms, legs, and back. The papules had become confluent into plaques. Subsequently, the patient revcovered. No further information is available.

Pt recv #1dose vax on 5/22/97;on 5/26/97 pt exp rash on arms & legs, angioedema of the upper lip & eyelids;5/30/97 pt exp itching; tx=Benadryl &Atarax w/ out help;pt exp aches &tingling in arms/ pt recv #2 vax 7/28/97;exp inc hives&itching Follow up report to previously submitted report on 03/01/1999: Information has been received from a physician concerning a 12 year old patient with cerebral palsy and had silastic and metal appliances in body who on 22-MAY-1997 was vaccinated with the first dose of hepatitis b vaccine recombinant. On 26-JUN-1997 the patient experienced a rash on arms and legs with no itching initially. In addition, the patient alos experience angioedema of the upper lip and eyelids upon wakening in the morning. It was noted that the patid did not have upper airway obstruction or increased work of breathing. approximately 4 days late, the patient experienced itching. The patient was seen by a physician who initially suspected arythema multiforme. Therapy with BENADRYL and ATARAX did not hpel with the itching. The patient then experienced aches and tingling in her arms. On 28-JUL-1997 the patient received the second dose of hepatitis b vaccine recombinant. Subsequently, an increase in hives and chronic itching was noted. On 30-JUL-1997, laboratory tests included erthrocyte sedmentation rate - 20, ANA - 1/160 ang GGT -17. The patient's thryroid function test were normal. The patient was diagnosied with chronic urticaria "with some relief" with ATARAX. As of 16-SEP-1998 the patient's experiences persisted. The urticaria was considered to be an other medical event. Follow-up information from a physician reported that in October of 1998, the patient recovered.
LAB_DATA: 7/30/97: Erythrocyte sedrate-20, ANA 1/160, GGT-17, Thyroid function-normal, WBC-5.2

Concomitant therapy included CLARITIN. It was reported that the patient received a booster dose of hepatitis b vaccine recombinant because he " supposedly had entire three dose series towice; however, the patient was not certain that one of the series was acutally the hepatitis b vaccine." The patient had a negative hepatitis v antibody titier before receiving the booster dose of hepatitis b vaccine recombinant. Approxmatley one hour post-vaccination, the patient developed a rash, wheezing, and swelling of the lips and face. The patient took BENADRYL and TAGAMET and went to an emergency room. subsequently, the patient recovered and went home. The patient was not admitted to the hospital. Follow-up information from a registered nurse reported on 11-JAN-1999 she spoke with the patient who reported he "had a red, puffy face and then wheezing followed by a rash every 7 to 10 days. These reactions were releived with BENADRYL." Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 9FEB99 pt devel a high fever & then began to seize;pt was taken to  hosp where blood & urine testing were done on IV ATB & therapy started;pt was discharged same day. This is in follow-up to report(s) previously submitted on 5/21/99. Information has been received from a physician concerning a 16-month-old Caucasian male with stable reactive airway disease and a history of otic infection. Who on 29-JAN-1999 was vaccinated SC in the right arm with first dose of MMR II; concomitant vaccine that same day included PEDVAXHIB. On 09-FEB-1999 the patient developed high fever and then began to experience seizures and was taken to the emergency room. He was placed on IV antibiotic therapy, several laboratory testing were performed. Laboratory tests reveal the following results: CO2 = 19.0 NEQ/L; WBC = 21.5 K; LYMPH = 17.0 %. The reporter also noted that the patient was kept in the emergency room for duration of 12 hours. Upon medicail review, it was determined that febrile seizure was an important medical event. The patient recovered from all the symptoms on 09-FEB-1999. No further information is available.
LAB_DATA: lymphocyte count, 17 %, Low; blood urea nitrogen, 21 MG/DL, High; total serum carbon, 19 NEQ/L, Low; WBC count, 21.5 K, High

pt exp  fever, h/a, dizzy x 13 days;13th day pt began twitching uncontrollably, head & mouth mainly;loss coherency;pt cont twitching, jerking, spasms;could not walk w/o falling;loss memory;urinate & soil self;dx ADHD & OCD;brain damage;Annual follow-up received on 10/19/00 provides no additional data. We explained everything that had been ocurring. He was very questionable about exactly what was occuring. He examined him and recommended we take him to a Pediatric Neurologist. He also ordered an immediate blood work-up. They tested him for many substances such as lead, chromium etc. Everything came out clear. He set us up with a neurologist. He said he couldn't see our son for over a month. We were extremely distraught. We argued over the severity of what was occuring. They said it was the best they could do. So we waited. Over this period of time our son deteriorated severly. He continued twitching, jerking, spasming. He could not even walk without falling. He lost his entire memory. He was like he was in a delierium. He would just sit and stare at a blank wall. He no longer recognized anything or anyone around him. He began urinating and soiling himself on a regular basis. He basically became like a vegatable. We called the doctor and pleaded for help. We were told we must wait. That there were other sick children too. This was the most horrible, stressful, sad experience in our lives. Our son could no longer talk at all. he had no memory of anything including his father and I. He had no potty training abilities. He had no co-ordination. He could barely walk. He would just sit and stare with his mouth open. After about 3 continuous weeks of twitiching it stopped. But his condition had no improvement. He became terrifed of anything. Screaming and crying uncontrollably. After about a week wait we finally got him to the neurologist. Upon him seeing and hearing our son. He says "why was this child not brought to my attention much sooner." We nearly went into hysterics. Explaining all we had been through and how hard we tried to get him in. He became upset and said he wished to speak to our sons pediatrition. So we agreed. He spoke to the doctor about him recognizing this as a DPT reaction. Why was this not brought to his attention sooner to begin treatment. Our sons pediatrition; said he just wasn't sure about the DPT reaction. He said he had observed some abnormal behaviors in our son before immunization; he thought it might relate to. We found this comment rude, offensive and a deliberate move to try and cover his huge mistakes. He had never brought any concerns about our son to our attention ever. He was his pediatrition since birth. He always commended us on his growth and advancements. Nothing but positive remarks. To hear this was infuriating. The neurologist asked for immediate admittance into the hospital. We agreed to this. He was admitted to the hospital. They did an MRI and a Spinal Tap. Both of the tests came back normal. The Neurologist said that our son had aquired an aphasia for a reason still unknown. So we should get an EEG The EEg should be sleeping. This was a problem because since all this occurred our son had become extremly hyper-active, rarely sleeping, he had constant laughing seizures which lasted for up to 3 hours. He was uncontrollable. We still tried the EEG. We could not get him to settle much less sleep for the test. The results were not showing seizure activity. The neurologist recommended taking him to a psycologist for evaluation. We agreed and upon doing so both evaluations brought up a possiblity of him aquiring a rare condition called Landau Kleffner Syndrome. They believed he was still having sub-clinical seziures. Which was causing the strange behaviors now occuring hyper-activity, social withdrawl, aggressiveness, depression etc. We felt it was because of the complete loss of speech and language and memory. That caused such tremdous frustration. During all this process the insurance company had refused to pay the medical bills for our son. They said that our son had been adversly affected by immunization. Therefore we needed to sue in this matter. We needed to sign a lein form stating that the insurance company would be reimbursed for any and all payments made by them from the date of his injury on. If we were to receive a settlement. We were more stressed and confused. Medical bills mounting, still no answers for our sons deterioration. We contacted a lawyer to see about getting the insurance to pay the bills they were legally liable to pay. In this process the lawyer had to obtain medical records and billing statements from all involved in his treatment. At this time our son had reached a level of unbelievable out of control aggression. Our entire family was crying and worried. We finally decided to see his pediatrition again about the problem. He prescribed PROZAC for our son. We agreed and administered the medication. Our sons behaviors did come under better control. But he could still not talk or even think clearly. We were taking him to a speech pathologist to help him. The neurologist he was seeing had requested we get another MRI and a sleeping 24hr. EEG, and a PET scan. We had accomplished a second MRI when he received papers from the attorney. He then became beligerant and seemed unwilling to help us further. We were devastated and explained we were only trying to get the insurance to pay our bills. He was rude and did not believe us. He said some very rude remarks and refused to run tests on our son. We then learned from the psycologist we were taking our son to see that his pediatrition had been saying very rude remarks about our son to the psycologist and other care givers. After he received attorney papers on our sons behalf. He was suddenly telling people that he always saw our son as "A weird kid" to quote him. This was the last thing we could tolerate from him. We refused to ever take our son to him ever again. We asked all the people in the process of helping him to no longer send any reports or Information to doctor. We were so worried and lost at this point. His pediatrition since birth was no longer available. Our son was still so sick and disturbed. We had no answers or help to get our boy back. Everyone had felt that these new disturbing behaviors were probably causedby sub-clinical seizures. We searched for a while and heard about a really good child psychiatrist who diagnosed and dealth with children having many symptoms like our son. So we took him to seem him. Immediately upon examing him he felt we also were dealing with sub-clinical seizures. He ordered a spect scan for our son. Which was scheduled as soon as possible. When he received the spect scan it showed he was definatly still having sub-clinical seizures. He had been experiencing them every since he had received his DPT. Because of the extended period of time he had suffered from these severe seizures in his front temporal lobes. This had caused the memory loss. The loss of speech. The odd behaviors such as huge mood swings. Now we know that our damage to both his left and right front temporal lobes. The thing that saddens us the most is that we know the damage could have been much less if he had gotten immediate attention and diagnosis like we basically begged for. Now he goes through extensive speech and language therapy. We work with him constantly he is making much progress. But he is a completely different child now. He has such a hard time with the simplist of tasks. he is on medicinal therapy form the psychiatrist. He has to take DepaKene for seizure control. The damage to his brain has also caused him to now have two other disorders diagnosedone is called ADHD or attention deficit hyper-activity disorder. Which he has to take a medication for. The other disorder is called OCD or obsessive compulsive disorder. Which he has to take a third medication for. Our lives have been turned upside down. It is so difficult; but we love him dearly and will continue to do what we can to help him
LAB_DATA: 2MRI's, 1 spinal tap, 1EEG, 1 spect scan,  1 extensive blood workup

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt recv vax on 8/11/98; on 8/20/98 pt exp fever x 2 days, raised/blanched/purple &red rash on legs to arms, fussy, local petechiae, runny nose &cough;tx=Advil & Elocon; dx=cutaneous lymphoid hyperplasia-follicular pattern. This is in follow-up to report(s) previously submitted on 5/21/99. Information has been received from a registered nurse concerning a 12-month-old male with a medical history of sensitive skin and aquagenic urticaria, who on 11-Aug-1998 was vaccinated SC with the first dose of MMR II in the right arm. Concomitant vaccinations that same day included the first dose of VARIVAX. On 20-Aug-1998 the patient developed a fever and a bilateral rash on his calves. On approximately 26-Aug-1998 the patient developed a rash on his arm and by 28-AUG-1998 the patient had developed a lacy raised rash on both calves. The patient was also noted as being fussy. The rash persisted through 03-OCT-1998 and the patient was then evaluated by a dermatologist. Follow-up information received from a physician indicated on 22-AUG-1998 the patient developed a fever for two days. He also developed a rash on his calves. On 28-AUG-1998 the patient developed a fever x 1 day and the rash spread to his arms and was described as raised and blanched. On 01-SEP-1998 the patient was noted as being very fussy with faint localized petechia and was treated with ADVIL. On 28-SEP-1998 a lacy, raised rash was noted on both calves and was non-tender and blanched. Therapy with ELOCON was initiated. The patient was also noted as developing a runny nose and cough x 3 days. On 03-OCT-1998 the rash was on the legs and arms and was noted as purple and red. The patient was then referred to a dermatologist. Information received from the dermatologist indicated from medical notes on 06-OCT-1998 "probable Henoch-Schonlein purpura associated with vaccination. Consider atypical erythema multiforme or even a very unusual granuloma annulare. Patient should be worked up for any organ involvement associated with Henoch-Schonlein purpura, particularly renal disease, although he is asymptomatic at present. Biopsy not performed today because of the age of the child and inability to cooperate with procedure. Suggest a trail of BENADRYL every night at bed time to see if urticarial component of this dermatitis may be reduced. Consider biopsy if dermatitis continues to progress and patient becomes symptomatic." Medical notes from 17-NOV-1998 indicated a diagnosis of cutaneous lymphoid hyperplasia, follicular pattern of biopsy. In December, 1998 the patient was noted to have recovered. No further information is available.
LAB_DATA: Pt seen by dermatologist, skin culture of lower leg to reach dx; biopsy, 11/17/98, Diagnosed with "Cutaneous lymphoid hyperplasia";

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt recv vax on 2/2/99; on 2/3/99 pt exp dizziness, unable to walk, nausea, fatigue; tx=Meclizine; The vaccinee has no known drug allergies. Patient's medical history included positive PPD, genital warts, and unspecified allergies. Patient denied a history of lupus, Crohn's disease, and rheumatoid arthritis. There was no illness at the time of vaccination. Concomitant medications included cetirizine (Zyrtec). On February 2, 1999 12:00, the patient received the first "standard adult" IM-left deltoid done of LYMERIX for prophylaxis of Lyme disease. Approximately 8 hours later, February 2, 1999 the patient developed "extreme" dizziness, the inability to walk, nausea, vomiting, and fatigue. The physician reported that the dizzziness was treated with meclozine (Meclizine) but persisted. The patient was seen by a primary care provider, two HNT physicians and a neurologist who all told the patient  that the symptoms were a coincidence and they were not casually related to the vaccine (LYMErix). As of March 26, 2001 the vaccinee reported bilateral knee joint pain, which patient states was diagnosed as arthritis (NOS) by an orthopedist. The most recent information received on March 26, 2001 reported the outcome of the events as ongoing. The patient's symptoms have lessened, but "still has problems and is not the same since the vaccine." The adverse evens of 'dizziness' and 'arthritis (NOS)' do not meet ICN serious criteria, but are being submitted as an expedited report by FDA request per the June 28, 2000 letter.
HISTORY: Height: 66 ins; Weight: 150 lbs The vaccinee has no known drug allergies. His medical history included positive PPD, genital warts, and unspecified allergies. SYMPTOM_TEXT: pt recv vax 20JAN97 & leg swollen twice size & cried for 5hr;pt would not sleep & pulled legs to stomach;crying spell;on 3FEB97 jerking, to ER;6FEB99 to hosp Dx sz;pt cannot talk or feed herself, has balance problems,gets infections easily  Annual follow-up received on 9/22/00 states that the pt continues to have over 100 seizures per day. She does not talk and understands very little. All medication has failed. Follow-up information received 12-JUL-2002 identified and further described the patient's adverse events. Followiing clarification of the source documents, the primary suspect vaccine was changed from Tri-Immunol to Tetramune. A mother reported that her 4-month-old daughter who had developed a respiratory syncytial viral infection (following immunization with "RSV" (manufacturer unknown vaccine) and was treated with an unspecified medication at the end of December 1996, received her second doses of Tatramune and IPV vaccines on 20-JAN-1997. According to the patient's grandmother, the patient was seen by the physician for persistent RSV symptoms that day. The patient was afebrile and immunization were administered. Shortly therafter, the patient was taken to her grandmother's home where she reportedly experienced inconsolable, high-pitched screamint. Her legs had "doubled in size" and she pulled her legs up, as if in pain. Her crying resolved 5 hours later, she slept. Following these events, the patient had sleep disturbances and her sleeping pattern was "horrible". The patient now cried inconsolably for long periods of time and her eyes seemed "totally different, like someone scared." She was lethargic and id not "respond as before." Her mother reported that she did not recognize anyone; her personality slight jerking movements. A physician's appointment was made. That night, her jerking and crying worsened and she was taken to the emergency room. A diagnosis of colic was made. The physician's appointment was canceled; however, a short time later, the patient was requested to be seen in the office as soon as possible. Unspecified blood work was performed and the patient was admitted to the hosptial on 03-FEB-1997. An EEG was performed and a diagnosis of infantile spasms was made. The patient was treated with adrenocortiotropic hormone following her recovery from RSV. Numerous procedures and tests were performed including an MRI scan, "Spec" scan, lumbar puncture, CAT scan and metabolic and genetic testing. Results were not provided. According to the patient's grandmother, "nothing shows up". She was prescribed a ketogenic diet and has had a vague nerve stimulator inserted. She has been treted with unspecified medications. As of 24-APR-2001, the patient can walk and sit up. She cannot talk, and cognitively, she is 6 months of age. The patient is incontinent and cannot feed herself with a spoon. The patient has 20 to 100 seizures per day. The grandmother indicated that the treating physician did not think the patient would progress any further than she has. The patient's "eyes and brain do not work correctly." Her daughter was "braindamaged." This report was directly submitted to VAERS by the reporter. A copy of this report has been forwarded to Aventis Pasteur, manufacturer of IPV. See NCN: HQ0118425APR2001.

pt child recv vax & pt went to bed w/chills, body aches, bad back pain & had one spot on side under arm;red & painful;broke out w/less than 100 spots vesicles;sore throat, chest pain;itching;could not sleep @ noc;dx chickenpox; 02/11/2010 Information has been received concerning an otherwise health 35 year old male patient who was exposed to his son (vaccinated on 06-FEEB-1998 with one dose of VARIVAX). On 13-MAR-1998 the patient "went to bed with chills, body aches, bad back pain and had on spot on his side, under his arm". The spot was described as bein "like his son's first spot (WAES 98032271) in that it was "worse, red and painful". On 14-MAR-1998 the patient "continued to feel beat up and when he went ot shave, he noticed that he had broken out with less than 100 spots all over his chest, back, nec, face, and scalp". He also experienced sore throat and chest pain. THe patietn was seen by a physician. A chest x-ray was obtained and the patient was prescribed acyclovir 800 mg. On the after noon of 15-MAR-1998, " the aches began to subside, itching began and he could not sleep at night". On 16-MAR-1998 the patient was "very itchy and was totally covered with spots that looked clearly like chickenpox", He was seen again by a physician who agreed with the diagnosis of chickenpos. On 11-MAR-1998 preliminary results of PCR analysis revealed Oka/Merck vaccine strain ant that a throat swab was negative VZV. It was also reported that the patient's skin lesions were healing, however, "he has developed oral lesions which the physican has diagnosed as varicella lesions". The physician also stated, as fas he knew, "the patient has no evidence of an alterd immune system and an HIV test was pending". Further additional information indicated that the treating physician " did not thing that this was a severe case of adult chickenpos, but the equivalent of a typical childhood case of chickenpox". Subsequently the patient's experiences were reported in a published literature article. It was noted that the patient developed varicella after exposure to his vaccinated child. No further information is available.
LAB_DATA: 3/14/98 CXR;3/24/98 lab test PCR analysis was Oka/Merck vaccine strain;lab test throat swab was negative for VZV;

aft vax pt exp slight stuffy/runny nose day later fuzzy all day/cold like sx. night congested, not sleep, diarrhea, loss appetite, days later spot on neck, quite red, hot to touch, 6spots 1in rectum irritated pt, bled, boil like see comment. Information has been received from a physician concerning a 1-year-old male patient who on 06-FEB-1998 was vaccinated with one dose of VARIVAX. Concomitant vaccination that same day included DTP. That same day, the patient experienced a "slightly stuffy runny nose (thought to be drooling)." On 07-FEB-1998 he was "fuzzy all day and had cold-like symptoms". It was reported that by that evening, "he was very congested and could not sleep at night." On 08-FEB-1998 the patient was seen by a pediatrician because "he was quite congested". The patient was prescribed Biaxin 250 mg "which that patient did not finish because it gave him such terrible side effects as diarrhea, loss of appetite, etc". It was reported that "he hated it with passion no matter how it was given to him". On approximately 24-FEB-1998 he develop the first spot on his back. It was the largest becoming quite red, hot to the touch at night when he slept on it. This spot eventually scabbed over and was the last to disappear". On 25-FEB-1998 a second spot appeared on his neck. By approximately 27-FEB-1998 the patient had three more spots which appeared on his abdomen. It was reported that three never seemed to bother him and never scabbed over but just faded away. On 28-FEB-1998 an additional spot appeared in the patient's rectum which really irritated him and it bled a tiny bit when using wet wipes during diaper changes. By 01-MAR-1998 the spot on his back was still pretty bad looking and his grandmother thought it resembled a boil and should be checked in case he was fighting something internal. On 02-MAR-1998 the patient was seen by a physician who did not consider chickenpox since the patient had the vaccine and the spots looked remarkably better. The physician thought the spots may have been just bug bites but prescribed Cefzil 250 mg for fluid in the ear which would also clear up anything else he might have had. The patient's father was reported as well (WAES 98031937). Follow-up information from a physician indicated that the patient also developed a varicella-like rash. On an unspecified date the patient recovered. No further information is available.

p/vax pt devel an outbreak of chickenpox w/8 lesions on the chest & under the arm;medical attention was sought; Follow up information received. On July 20, 1998, the patient's mother called the physician's office to notify them that her child was sent home from daycare due to fluid filled lesions. The patient was seen in the physician's office on July 23, 1998. She was afebrile with no change in appetite. She was sleeping okay. The rash was described as papular on arms, face and chest. Was diagnosed with a viral rash and the plan was observation.  On an unspecified date, the patient recovered. Follow up information was received from a health care professional who reported that the patient's mother called the physician's office to report that her child had 4-5 red bumps on her back which were confirmed by the daycare as chickenpox. This is in follow-up to report (s) previously submitted on 05/14/1999. Information has been received from a health care porfesional concerning a 4 year old female patient who on 05-Jun-1998 was vaccinated with the first dose of VARIVAX. 0.5 ml in the left arm. Subsequently the patient developed herpes roster, with clusters of vesicles on the left arm, left hand and left side. As of 05-Aug-1998 the patient had no new lesions. On 06-Aug-1998 the patient presented for a follow up visit. The rash was described as "very strange and unusual". The patient had a "big vesicle" on her palm, and several additional clusters of vesicles on the inside of her arm extending to the elbow. Once the clusters reached the elbow area, the line of clusters began to wrap around the arm, and wre located on the back side of the upper arm. The patient also had some dry lesions on the left side of her neck and lower back. She indicated that there were "dry ptaches" around most of the vesicular clusters; however the reporter was unable to lift any acaba from these areas. The lesions were "purplish" in color. The patient had itching, but no pain, and was afebril. The patient's mother thought that her daughter had poison ivy and treated her with WESTCORT and AVEENO. On 06-Aug-1998 a sample was obtained from avesicular lesion for PCR analysis. The results of the speciment revealed the OKA/MERCK vaccine strain virus. Subsequnetly, the child recovered fully. No further information is available.
LAB_DATA: lab test: 8/6/98, deoxyribonucleic acid, PCR analysis of amplified VZV DNA, 1st, 2nd, 3rd runs, OKA/MERCK

pt recv vax during 2 week "break" from steroid tx for hx reactive airway; restarted steroids 1 1/2 weeks a/ sx occurred; 18d p/ vax, presented w/ lesions; hosp w/ VZV pneumonia, decompensated, intubated-on vent; required 3 blood transfusion. This is an follow-up to report(s) previously submitted on 5/14/1999. Information has been received from a health care professional concerning a 5-year-old male patient who in 1998 was vaccinated with one dose of VARIVAX. Approximately ten days following vaccination, the patient experienced a rash (time frame unknown) and was eventually hospitalized with VZV pneumonia. At the time of the report, the patient was on a ventilator in the PICU. It was reported that in approximately 17-NOV-1998, DFA analysis of endotracheal secretions was done for CMV, HSV, flu A and B and RSV, all of which were negative; however, DFA for VZV was "strongly positive." In addition, specimens were "negative for sycoplasm IgM." Additional information received indicated that in approximately 17-NOV-1998, results of PCR analysis from an endotracheal specimen were positive for vaccine strain varicella zoster virus. It was also reported that the patient recovered and was discharged. The patient had a history of reactive airway disease and the physician believed the patient had been on a course of steroids 10 days prior to vaccination. The patient "did have a rash on admission however, it was not severe. However, the patient did decompensate quickly from a respiratory perspective and required intubation with ventilator assist. The patient required ventilatory support for approximately 6 weeks. The physician did not know if the patient acquired a noseomial infection while on the ventilator which would have complicated the patient's course." Further additional information indicated that the child has "severe cerebral palsy (due to an abruption at birth)." The child is competely homebound and requires total care. Also, his concomitant therapy at the time of vaccination included Tegretol, Clonopine, Rhinocort and albuterol. It was reported that the patient "has a long term history of intermitent steroid use due to his severe reactive airway disease, but he was not actually on steroids at the time of vaccination. "As of of 08-OCT-1998 the patient was in the middle of a steroid taper, which was completed on approximately 15-OCT-1998. On 22-OCT-1998 the child "had been off steroids for a week and was vaccinated with VARIVAX. " He started again on steroids on 29-OCT-1998 and on 09-NOV-1998 he presented to the doctor's office with lesions and subsequently was hospitalized due to VZV pneumonia. Follow-up information from a physician reported that on 22-OCT-1998, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of Influenza virus vaccine. In addition, it was reported that the patient was hospitalized from 09-NOV-1998 through 02-JAN-1999. While hospitalized, the patient received three transfusions. Subsequently, the patient recovered. Additional follow-up information from a physician reported that the patient's usual dose of steroid was 1-2 mg/kg/day (2 tsps BID) of Pediapred. On 29-OCT-1998, the patient was again started on 1-2 mg/kg/day (2 tsps) of Pediapred twice daily for 5 days. Subsequently in October 2003, the patient's experience was also reported in a published literature article. The article also mentioned three other patient's (WAES # 96031140, 98101671 and 00120881) with similar experiences following exposure to VARIVAX. No further information is available.

Information has been received from a medical assistant concerning a 74 year old female with a history of urticarle and with a codeine allergy who on 26-JAN- 1999 was vaccinated in the left deltoid with PNEUMOVAX 23. Follow-up was received froma physician which indicated the patient also experienced discomfort. No further information is available.

Information has been received from a registered nurse concerning a 23-year-old Caucasian female patient with multiple sclerosis and gastrointestinal sensitivity to erythromycin who on 02-APR-1999 was vaccinated with a first dose of PNEUMOVAX 23 in the left deltoid. That evening, the patient experienced arm soreness in the vaccinated arm. On 01-APR-1999 the patient experienced a sore and throbbing arm, chills, and a low grade temperature of 100.4 degrees F. On 04-APR-1999 the patient's temperature was 102.2 degrees F. and the arm was very sore, achy, and throbbing. Early that afternoon, in the area 1 1/2 to 2 inches below the injection site there appeared three red blotches. The arm was swollen from the shoulder to above the elbow. The patient also experienced mild headache with fever. That eveving, the three red patches connected together. The low grade temperature persisted at that time. The red spot was sore to the touch. The patient experienced loose stools that evening. At 2:00 AM on 04-APR-1999, the patient threw up. On 05-APR-1999, the patient presented to a physician and was diagnosed with "febrile reaction to PNEUMOVAX 23. All symptoms except red patch area dissipated throughout the day 05-APR-1999. Some redness on arm was still present on 12-APR-1999." Another patient was reported with adverse experiences following vaccination with PNEUMOVAX 23 (WAES98040468). Additional information has been requested.

Information has been received from a registerd nurse concerning an 18 year old female who on 02-APR-1999 was vaccinated with PNEUMOVAX 23. That evening, the patient experienced chills. On 03-APR-1999 in the morning the patient experienced arm soreness, it hurt to use the arm. On 04-APR-1999 the patient experienced a fever of 101.7 degrees F. At 3:00 PM that day the patient experienced red patches 3 inches below the site of injection. She took ibuprofen and TYLENOL. She also experienced back, head, and neck soreness. On 04-APR-1999 the patient also experienced fever of 100.7 degrees and sore muscles. Her arm hurt from the shoulder down. On 05-APR-1999 the patient experienced redness and induration at the site of injection, nausea and pulse was 112. An EKG on 05-APR-1999 was normal. That afternoon, the patient's temperature was 102.7  degress F. and the soreness persisted. The patient receoverd from the red patches below the injection site on 05-APR-1999. At the time of the report, the patient has a fever of 99 degrees F. and the headaches and the arm pain persisted. Another patient was reported with adverse experiences following vaccination with PNEUMOVAX 23 (WAES 99040466). No further information is available.

p/vax pt exp pain in knees; ankles; wrists; seen by MD; tx w/ibuprofen; condition ongoing.  The patient has seasonal allergies, and no drug allergies. Concomitant medication: tetanus vaccine administered on 03-Mar-99 and Beconase nasal spray. On 03-Mar-99 the patient received the first .5 cc dose of LYMERIX and the unspecified dose of tetanus vaccine. Twelve days later, on 15-Mar-99, the patient experienced pain in knees, ankles, and wrists, and was seen by a physician. He was treated with ibuprofen 400 mg bid on 15-Mar-99. On 26-Mar-99 his ibuprofen dosage was increased to 600 mg bid. Nine days later, on 24-Mar-99, the patient developed inflamatory polyarthritis and plantar fascitis. Testing has not revealed a specific diagnosis. As of 21-May-99, the patient stated that he was doing well; He had some slight discomfort in his right ankle. He compared it to the feeling one would have had after having sprained an ankle several months ago. It has not kept him from doing anything. He did not think that any joint were swollen, ad, or warm. he no longer had significant heel pain. He was back to work full-time and was taking no medications. Examination showed no swollen joints, including the righ ankle. He was no longer tender under the heels. Impression: acute inflamatory arthritis and plantar fascitis, resolved. Etiology unclear although probably related to the Lyme Vaccine. The most recent information, received on 01-Oct-99, reports the condition of the patient as resolved.

p/vax pt had sore arm; devel sore neck, got tired; sore leg muscles; no appetite & sl stomach cramps; Case, reference number 1999009261-1, is a spontaneous report from a mother referring to her 16 year old son. No allergies, medical history, or concomitant medications. The patient had received three hepatitis B doses and the flu vaccine in the past without any problems. On 24-Mar-99, the patient received the first IM dose of LYMERIX for prevention of LYME disease. 20 seonds later, on 24-MAR-99, he had a sore arm, which lasted four days. Subsequently, he developed a sore neck, which lasted two days, got tired for 7-10 days or more. He had sore leg muscles which lasted two days or more. He had no appetite and slight stomach cramps for at least seven days. All symptoms resolved in April, 1999, within two weeks of receiving LYMERIX. The most recent information, received on 08-Feb-00, reports the condition of the patient resolved.

Case reference number 1999012419-1 is a spontanous report from a nurse practitioner referring to a 40 year old female. At the time of the event, the patient was taking EFFEXOR. On 20-May-1999, the patient received her first treatment with LYMERIX at an unspecified dose for prophylaxis. Approximately 3 hours later, the patient returned to the clinic with complaints of left arm joint pain that radiated to her neck. The pain possibly involved the subacromial burs below the left deltoid. Also, the patient experienced nausea. LYMERIX was discontinued. The recent information received on 20-May-1999 reports the symptoms are ongoing. The most recent information, received on 05-Oct-99 reports the condition of the patient is unknown.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: p/vax pt c/o weight loss; arthritis symptoms; h/a; tiredness & upset stomach; took ADVIL; it helped a little; Medical record of April 27, 1999 noted that the patient complained of pain in both breasts. The diagnosis was "rule out breast mass". April 3, 2000 medical record noted "lumpy left breast". The vaccinee was diagnosed with "rule out breast mass" and PREMPRO was prescribed. May 2, 2000 physical therapy note: The vaccinee complained of pain in both hands, lumbar spine, both hips, both feet, toes, callus muscles, adn forearm muscles. Patient also had a "constant" headache and weak grip. The vaccinee stated that these symptoms were caused by "medication". The vaccinee had positive myofascial restrictions, normal upper and lower extremity range of motion, and normal ankle strength. May 30, 2000 physical therapy report: the vaccinee received six sessions of physical therapy. Treatment protocol consisted of soft tissue techniques, range of motion, stretching, moist heat, "E-stim", paraffin to bilateral hands, home exercise program, and a comprehensive stretching and strengthening pool program. At discharge, the vaccinee reported good/bad days. Pain complaints fluctuated in intensity and region. Objectively, active range of motion was normal throughout all tested regions. Gross strength was within functional limits. Special testing revealed scoliosis. Myofascial restrictions were significant throughout T/&/L/S (thoracic and lumbar spine) At discharge, the vaccinee was encouraged to manage her condition with stretching and strengthening, including a pool program. It was recommended that patient perform light impact activities, i.e. walking, swimming, for cardiovascular fitness. Recommendation: discharge with home exercises program. June 29, 2000 medical record noted"vaginal lump". The vaccinee was diagnoses with left Bartholin abscess and underwent marsupialization of the left Bartholin abscess on July 1, 2000. The patient tolerated the procedure well. The Bartholin biopsy abscess showed "fragments of fibroconnective tissue with acute and chronic inflammation; no epithelial lining seen." Please note that the events of "lumpy breast mass" and "Bartholin abscess" were not reported as adverse events due to vaccine administration, but were found during the course of review of the patient's health records. Therefore they are not listed as adverse events. As of June 12, 2001, the outcome of the events is unknown. The adverse events of 'headache' and 'osteoarthritis' do not meet ICN serious criteria, but are being submitted as an expedited report by special FDA request per the June 28, 2000 letter. Follow up received 7/2001.
LAB_DATA: 12  April  2000 bilateral mammogram: Impression: There was no evidence of malignant disease or of significant interval change since May 1999. Because of the history of severe left breast pain, the possibility of radiographically occult cysts, for example cannot be excluded due to the dense paronchymal pattern and if symptoms persisted, an ultrasound study might be useful to further evaluate the breast. Continued annual mammographic screening was advised. May 12, 1999 sonohysterogram: There was a focal area of altered echogenicity in the posterior aspect of the fundus measuring roughtly 2.0 x 2.0 x 1.8 cm, most consistent with a leiomyoma. The known posterior leiomyoma did not seem to create a contour deformity of the intrauterine cavity as visualized. Impression: No focal abnormalities of the endometrial cavity were identified. July 1, 2000 Bartholin abscess biopsy: fragments of fibroconnective tissue with acute and chronic inflammatory; no epithelial lining seen. Biopsy, May 12, 1999, Result Test: Benign left breast biopsy. Sonohysterogram, May 12, 1999, No focal agnormalities of the endometrial cavity
OTHER_MEDS: KLONOPIN; PREMARIN; CYCRIN; PAMELOR; aspirin; PREMPRO; VIOXX; glucosamine chondroitin
HISTORY: depression; panic attacks; anxiety, respiratory disease, breast disease (microcalcifications), chronic hand pain secondary to sewing which stopped when patient stopped sewing, thoracic spine scoliosis, arthritis, tubal ligation (1981), possible osteoporosis, left knee skiing injury, bone deformity (thenar eminences), unspecified distal interphalangeals deformity and 36-pound weight change. Patient has been a smoker (one pack per day for 42 years; sometimes did not smoke and used nicotine gum, patch or inhaler instead). The vaccinee had run all her life; reported ran only short distances. PREMARIN, CYORIN, KlLONOPIN, aspirin, PREMPRO, glucosamine/chondroitin and PAMELOR The vaccinee has no drug allergies. Follow up received 7/01. Left breast biopsy, microcalcifications.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: p/vax pt exp arthritis sx (achiness & swelling) in hips, knees, ankles;also exp flu-like sx;saw rheumatologist & underwent blood test & x-rays;rheumatologist stated had reactive arthritis;tx w/meds; Report 1999013144-1 describes reactive arthritis in a 47-year-old female who received an injection of LYMERIX.  This report was received from the vaccinee.  Follow-up information was received from a nurse practitioner.  Medical records were received as part of litigation proceedings.  Additional information was received from a newpaper reporter.  Concurrent medical conditions included severe premenstrual syndrome, fluid retention, penicillin allergy, family history of rheumatoid arthritis, arthritic pain in fingers and knee caps when taking MEGACE and ALDACTARIDE in 1987, and flu-like symptoms while taking ALDACTARIDE in 1987.  Aldactaride was discontinued on 04 June 1987.  Surgical history included two full-term ceserean sections and tubal ligation.  On 04 May 1999, the patient received her first 30 mcg injection of LYMERIX.  Approximately one to two weeks later, the patient reportedly experienced joint pain in her hips, knees, and ankles; flu-like symptoms; ankle edema; swollen feet; a viral syndrome, and stifness (NOS).  She "could scarcely walk up and down stairs."  The patient reported that she saw a rheumatologist and underwent unspecified blood tests and x-rays.  The patient stated that the rheumatologist said she had "reactive arthritis".  Medical records from the patient's gynecologist and gynecoendocrinologist indicated that the patient was complaining of multiple arthralgias at a 06 May 1999 office visit.  Antinuclear antibody titer and rheumatoid factor measured on 17 May 1999 were negative.  The patient had elevated eosinophils 7.4% (normal, 0-5%), elevated monocytes 600/cubic millimter (normal, 0-590/cubic millimeter), and elevated globulins 3.4 gm/dL (normal, 1.3-3.4 gm/dL).  The symptoms were treated with an anti-inflammatory (NOS), steroids, CELEBREX 100 mg twice daily for 1.5 weeks, and RELAFEN 750 mg every 12 hours. The information received on 09 June 1999 reported the pain was less severe, but the swelling presisted.  The informatoin received on 31 January 2001 did not provide an outcome.  In a news article published 25 June 2001, a reporter stated, "The stiffness and swelling has become so severe that she is dependent on anti-inflammatory drugs to keep her mobile."  The patient stated, "I just keep moving.  It doesn't get rid of the pain, but it keeps me from stiffening." The outcomes of the flu-like symptoms and viral syndrome were not provided.  The adverse events of reactive arthritis and joint pain do not meet ICH serious criteria, but are being submitted as an expedited report by special FDA request per the June 28, 2000 letter.  Follow up information received July 17, 2001. In 1977, the patient began to experience discomfort in legs. Atrophy of the lateral aspect of her right thigh was noted. Although patient is left-handed and left-side dominant, her left thigh was smaller than her right thigh. The physician stated, "lesion may be bilateral." The physician recommended consideration of electromyelogram, exercise, and weight loss. On May 27, 1999, Lyme IgG/IgM ratio was 1.34 (positive, 1.10 or greater).

p/vax pt exp arthus phenomenon on a total of four occasions p/both lymerix doses respectively;tics were on for a short period of time (1-4 hours) producing this phenomenon;pt exp erythema migrans;pt condition outcome unk; Case, reference number 1999013677-1, is a spontaneous report from a 66 year old male physician/consumer and a physician. Allergic to penicillin. No medical history, or concomitant medications. No illness at the time of vaccination. On unspecified dates, the patient received the first and second IM-left deltoid doses of LYMERIX for prevention of Lyme disease. The patient experienced possible Arthus phenomenon on a total of four occasions within a few hours after both LYMERIX doses, respectively. Tics were on for a short period of time (1-6 hours) producing this phenomenon. A long lasting reaction (local reaction weeks up to more than one month at injection site) was experienced. The patient developed a localized area of induration without fever, chills, or arthritis. He also experienced erythema migrans, and intense itching. Patient stated that he had imperfect protection with LYMERIX. The physcian/consumer attributed this reaction to LYMERIX but when it was pointed out that the chance of being bitten by four infected ticks at the same time was extremely small, he realized that this was not probable, and concluded that these were local reactions to a tick bite possibly due to a reaction to tick saliva but probably not true Arthus reactions and not related to LYMERIX. The patient's physician stated that symptoms had an incomplete resolution. There is still itching at the sites. The most recent information, received on 10-Nov-99, reports the outcome of the patient as ongoing.

A patient reported that she received an injection of FLU SHIELD (1995-96 formula) in 1996 and , subsequently developed a "migratory" rash which was itchy and oozed when scratched. She developed 2 infections as a result of scratching the rash. The patient has been taking prednisone since 1996 for the rash, and is currently being treated with ultraviolet light therapy which "seems to be helping a bit". This patient was recently diagnosed with an allergy to thimerosal. The patient also reported this event to a local health regulatory agency (Ref. no. U1999-00347). She told the agency that she was immunized in the fall of 1995. She also told the agency that thimerosal allergy was diagnosed by skin bispsy and patch testing. she said she had a past history of hepatitis (type not specified). Altough she specifically told Wyeth-Ayerst that she had received no vaccines within 4 weeks of FLU SHIELD, she told the agency that she had received tetanus toxoid and pneumococcal vaccine within 4 weeks of FLU SHIELD.  Follow-up information received from a physician on 30-NOV-1999 indicated that patch testing resulted in a "mild reaction" to thimerosal. Skin biopsy performed on 04-MAY-1999 "showed allergic contact dermatitis which could not be secondary thimersol given time frame." The patient has stasis dermatitis which improves when she is complaint with therapy. She also has intermittent eczema flares that are "not related to thimerosal injection 3 years ago."
LAB_DATA: Unknwon 05/04/1999, Biopsy NOS, allergic contact dermatitis; Skin test NOS positive, mild reaction to thimersol

p/vax mom reported child lost all feeling in arms from below the elbow down;It wasn't like a tingling, you could stick a pin into them & there was no rxn;pt unable to walk in wheelchair;dx of hysteria has been considered but not confirmed; Information has been received from a consumer concerning her 3-year-old daughter who on 24-Jul-1998 was vaccinated with one dose of RECOMBIVAX HB (site unknown). There were no concomitant medications. In November, 1998, shortly before Thanksgiving, the patient's mother reported that her daughter "least all feeling in her arms from below the elbow the down. That her daughter least all feeling in her arms from below the elbow down. It wasn't like a tingling, you could stick a pin into them and there was no reaction. On 16-DEC-1998 lost all feeling in her legs from knees down. In february 1999. The patient regained feeling in her arms, however, she has not regained the feeling in her legs. The patient sought unspecified medical treatment. Follow-up information received from a health care professional indicated that this is an undiagnosed case. Several specialists have been unable to find anything wrong with the patient or confirm a diagnosis. At present, the patient is unable to walk and is in a wheelchair. The patient has been evaluated by numerous specialists, including a neurologist, gastroenterologist, and psychiarist, and all evaluations to date have been negative. The reporter noted child has been worked up form head to toe. A diagnosis of hysteria has been considered but has not been confirmed. The patient continues to undergo testing, and no formal diagnosis has been made. Upon medical review, the patient's condition was determined to be disabling. Additional information has been requested.

p/vax pt became SOB & had sx of wheezing & taken to hosp via automobile;while in car wheezing worse & mom stated passed out;noted to be hypotensive;devel petechiae & a spasmotic cough & urticaria;pt hosp in ICU;anaphyl rxn to vax per MD. Case, reference number 1998029981-1, is a spontaneous report from a medical assistant referring to a female patient aged 5 years. The patient's post medical history included a recent upper respiratory tract infection for which she was treated with amoxicillin and Naldecon DX. At the time of the event, the patient had allergic rhinitis and asthma with her triggers being excerise, strong fumes and animals. She was taking inital two puffs three times a day, and Proventil Inhaler on an as needed basis. On an unspecified date, the patient received her first injection with ENGERIX-B. On 08-Dec-1998, the patient received her second injection of ENGERIX-B 0.5 ml for prophylaxis for school regulations. She also received her MMR injection at the same time. Approximtely 15 minutes later the patient became short of breath and had symptoms of wheezing and was taken to the hospital via an automobile. While in the automobile, her wheezing worsened and her mother stated that she passed out. She was noted to be hypotensive upon arrival and developed petechiae and a spasmotic cough and urticaria. The patient was hospitalized in the Intensive Care Unit from 08-Dec-1998 to 09-Dec-1998. A hospital discharge summary is not available. The eventual diagnosis made on 08-Dec-1998 was an anaphylactic reaction. The patient was treated for the event with intravenous steroids, epinephrine and intravenous fluids. The most recent information received on 09-Dec-1998 reports the outcome of the patient as recovered and discharged from the hospital. Allergy consultation was performed with the opinion of the chief allergist that the patient had an anaphylactic reaction to either the MMR test or ENGERIX-B vaccination. Allergy testing of both these vaccinations was not to be performed at this time. If further doses were to be given, testing would be done at a future time. Skin testing was done and was positive for cockroach, dust mites, grasses, weeds and molds. Testing for egg by both RAST and skin was negative.
HISTORY: allergic rhinitis, asthma, URI;allergic rhinitis & asthma w/some day & noc time coughing;no food allergies;birth history is unremarkable;no somkers or pets in home;

p/vax pt exp a high temp lasting days;3/89 pt becam distant;showed no interest in interaction & began making strange hand movements & mannerisms;6/89 pt sleep patterns had been disrupted;became hyperactive & required little sleep;dx autism; Follow-up information received states the pt had been found to have "glue ears." His hearing fluctuates. Grommets were inserted in ears in 12/89, further testing was normal. Pt was retested 7/24/91 and was found to have reduced hearing again. At this same time the pt was not eating very well. He has a language delay. Mental examination revealed a 4-year old boy who appeared to be functioning at an 8-month-old level in all areas except locomotion. He did not appear to have a social deficit which is described in autism, eye contact was good and he would smile and play some baby games. No evidence of avoidance behavior. A child psychiatrist summarized his finding and felt the pt had a general developmental delay in all areas except locomotion. He didn't feel the child fit the category of childhood autism, but thinks th pt could be classified as having atypical autism which is the other term used for children with mental retardation with autistic features. Additional follow-up information from a foreign legal firm reported that the pt's parents completed an annual educational review of their son's progress for 1999. The parents note that there has not been change in their son's general health such as fitness, eating and sleeping habits, diet or medication. They felt that their son is generally happy and is able to cope better in crown situations and that his moods are more settled. The child uses photographs of places while their family is out and about. He seems more reassured to know what is going on.60 day follow-up / provided no additional data.
LAB_DATA: CT head-nml,  urine metabolic-nml, EEG-abnormal, routine biochemical screen-nml, diagnostic laboratory test-low iron

Normal rxn at site of shot. About to pass out in ER.  Rash. Rash still occurs when bathing, 6 wks later. Didn't feel this way until after vax and meds. Dr testing to see if allergic to shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Arm became very stiff & dvlped a high fever.Also dvlped sore throat & other cold symptoms.
Red, irritated & itchy area L/deltoid after receiving Td on 5/27/99. Some erythema & induration. Suspect allergic rxn vs cellulitis. Treated with E-mycin.
Pt dvlped atrophic dermatitis at site of injection. 4 cm x 4 1/2 cm darkened area dvlped-hypersensitive to palpation w/ discomfort.

11/2, notified by pt (an RN), of pain immediately at time of injection. States she was "shot too high". On 11/2, having aching, tingling "vibration feeling" and arm "irritable". On 11/3, still having symptoms.
Mother brought child in 12/15/99 for check of swelling/rash on L/thigh with apparent tenderness. Better with time (2 days). Broke out on 15th.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 12/18/99:Pt reported generalized urticaria,edema of lips & eyes, malaise.12/20/99:Pt tx w/ Prednisone.12/22/99:Dermatology visit; tx w/ Prednisone injection,Doxepin,& Claritin.12/23/99:Pt feeling better.

10 cm red raised area on left thigh.
12/7/99, Pt passed out at school after standing up. Eyes rolled back and hit head on floor. 911 called, unconscious for 15 secs, no jerking witnessed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Rcv'd vax and was very fussy dring night. Had vomiting episodes next day. Could not rule out superimposed viral illness w/ possible rxn to vax, D/T red/warm/knot at that vaccine site.
Rash on back, generalized, upper buttocks pink, temp 100.5, no resp distress.  Rxed Benedryl Resolved 10/28/99.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Two days post-vaccine, large blotchy rash, raised & itchy. Started on arm and spread to back, stomach, shoulders and other arm. Seen by MD on 12/3/99 and given Benadryl for allergic reaction, duration 18 days.

Pt woke up during the night w/raised rash, size of the hand all over body except on chest & face. Rash was like whelps. Dr said he thought it was a reaction from vax & started pt on Benadryl. Pt took it for 24 hrs & rash had gone by evening

By afternoon, pt had vomiting/diarrhea. Thought she had fever. Red and itching at site. Better on 11/25/99, then sx's started again on 11/26/99. Saw PMD who dx'd bacterial infection. Given antibiotic. Improved after that.
Father said pt developed swelling & redness around the injection site, which progressed and turned black/blue. He was treated at ER for Cellulitis. Now has a rash and blisters, according to father.

9 days post/vaccination w/temp to 102.6. Persistent temp 11 days post/vaccination w/erythematous papules just beginning, mostly on abdomen, back & GU area (15 lesions). Very suspiscous for beginning of varicella rash.
13 x 12 cm, erythema to L/deltoid.

The evening after shots, pt had aching muscles. He continues to have arm pain, usually at night. He states has some decreased ROM when he's having pain and a decrease in arm strength. He has continued complaint.

No rxn to 1st vax. 2nd dose exp urticaria. 1/29/99 3rd dose - fever, gen erythemia, prolonged urticaria. 8/18/99 pt seen at hosp urticaria spreads all over body. Fever and gen erythemia. Prescribed Hydroxyzine 10mg PO tabs PRN.
